column12: APPARATUS FOR ROTATING A HEATED CYLINDRICAL VESSEL OR SHELL OF A DRUM AND WITH A MINIMUM OF HEAT TRANSFER TO A DRIVING ELEMENT
Plug-in coupling for container - consists of reception ring inserted into container and coupling section attached to lead
column13: The plug-in coupling is built into the wall of a container. It is connected to a lead or hosepipe. There is a reception ring inserted into the wall of the container and a coupling section attached or attachable on to the lead, or hosepipe. The coupling section (10) is shaped like a cylindrical case (11) ending in one area in fingers positioned at equal distances from the circumference. Each finger (13) has at its front end a section (15) extending at an incline with the end of the finger located at the narrow end of the inclined surface and with the further end of the inclined surface forming a shoulder (16) outside the plane of the finger. The reception ring has a bore extending at an incline the wider end of which being that into which the coupling section is pressed in and having a wider dia. than the OD bordered by the ends of the fingers.

column12: Life Saving Apparatus applicable to Tram, Motor, Cable and other Cars and Vehicles
column13: 9930. Carr, J. April 30. Obstruction-removers.-An obstruction - remover for tramcars, motor cars, cable cars, and the like is formed by a tray or shoot A, Fig. 1, supported between brackets B by studs D, D on the tray entering slots or grooves C, C in the brackets. Either or both of the slots in each bracket are inclined so that, when an obstruction causes the tray to move backwards, the tray dips downwards at the front and lifts the obstruction. The studs D may have rollers on them to reduce fricticn. Guards F may be placed at the sides of the tray to prevent the brackets B from striking the obstruction. In a modification, shown in Fig. 6, the tray has only one stud D at each end and is counterweighted to rest normally on a bar G.

A rotary assembly for rotating a vessel such as a rotary kiln with a minimum amount of heat transfer to the driving element. A pluraltiy of coupling assemblies are provided which include a first bracket attached to the vessel. Pivotally connected to the bracket is a link member having an opposite pivot point on the driving element. With the coupling arrangement, heat from the inner rotating element which causes different rates of thermal expansion with respect to the girth gear does not produce high stresses on either element.

column12: An Improved Fender or Wheel Guard for Tram Cars Motor Cars and such like Vehicles
column13: 25,780. Carr, J. Nov. 24. Obstruction-removers.-Relates to obstructionremovers for tramcars, motor cars, and the like, and especially to obstruction-removers of the kind described in Specification No. 9930, A.D. 1902. A tray E, Fig. 1, is supported by stud rollers F, F working in slots D, D in brackets C fixed to the pilot board A. The slots are so formed that, when the tray strikes an obstruction, it moves backwards, and the front edge dips down near to the ground. In order to make the tray act more quickly, it is fitted with springs S, and a gate I is hung from the front of the car and connected by a rod R to a lever P which normally holds the tray in its horizontal position. The lower end Q, Fig. 4, of the lever P is formed as a catch to engage a pin M connected to the tray by links L and working in slots in a fixed bracket O. When the gate is pushed backwards, the catch Q is released from the pin M, and the springs S operate the tray E. The tray may be supported by short links instead of by stud rollers working in slots.

A New or Improved Level and Clinometer.
column13: 4040. Carr, T. J. Feb. 18. Clinometers; levels.-A combined spirit-level and clinometer particularly applicable for setting up horizontal and vertical shafting, comprises a V-shaped base 3 and a hinged spirit-level 1, which is so mounted that it may be fixed parallel or at rightangles to the base, and in. some cases, at any intermediate angle thereto. In the instrument shown in Fig. 1, the level is secured in the two positions for setting up horizontal or vertical shafting by means of extensions 5, 7 at right-angles to each other, which engage with bolts 4 in the base. The level may move over a graduated sector 10, Fig. 4, a pointer 11 being provided to indicate the inclination of the base to the horizontal. Instead of employing a central clamping-screw 12, the sector may be formed with an arc-shaped slot, which receives a clamping-screw carried by the level.

column12: Improvements in Selfacting Weft Replenishing Apparatus for Looms for Weaving.
column13: 14,803. Carr, J. W. June 28, 1906, [date applied for under Patents Act, 1901]. Loom shuttles, changing bobbins and the like in, automatically.-The cop &c. magazines in automatic weft-replenishing looms, such as those described in Specifications Nos. 7161 and 7161<A>, A.D. 1905, consist of endless aprons formed by bars 4, Fig. 6, provided with spring jaws 5 and saddles 6 for the cops and with studs or hooks 7 for securing the thread ends. Round pins or other projections 8, which may be furnished with rollers, are provided on the carrier ends. They are guided in endless grooves 11, Fig. 1, in the inner faces of side frames 9, 10, bolted together. Each side frame may be formed in two parts, which are bolted together. Each apron is driven by sprocket-wheels 20, which are correctly pitched to engage the projections 8 and are mounted on a shaft 18 carrying a ratchetwheel 24, driven by a pawl 31 on a three-armed lever 38, when the weft fails and weft-changing is to occur. In this case, a lever 43, Fig. 4, is moved sideways into engagement with a cam, as described in the Specification referred to above, whereby a rod 32 and a finger or lever 39 are raised and the lever 38 is turned, so that the pawl moves back over the ratchet teeth. The finger 39 passes through a slot in a plate 42 on the lay at the first beat-up ; but, on the descent of the rod 32, the plate actuates the lever 39 on a subsequent beat-up. The shaft 18 is thus turned, its movement being limited by a spring bearing on a scalloped wheel fixed on the shaft, so that the apron is accurately advanced by one division. A gripper on a rocking shaft, which is turned through a quarter of a revolution for each actuation of the cop magazine, feeds the cops from the magazine into the shuttle box, a saddle or cradle on a rod adjustably fixed in a standard on the rocking shaft being used to support cops of varying diameters.

column12: Improvements in Apparatus for Actuating Signals on Railway Engines and the like from the Track.
column13: 12,435. Carr, J. G. May 29. Contacts, electric.-A transversely-sliding wedge on the track is moved into and out of the path of a vertically-sliding rod on the engine which releases a spring-operated switch to close a bell circuit. The wedge E sliding in guides F on the track is moved by the wire from the signal cabin, and is replaced by the counterweight B. The rod Q sliding in guides on the locomotive has a curved foot-piece T provided with a roller V. The rod Q on being lifted by contact with the wedge E moves the spring -controlled lever M about its pivot against the action of the spring N<1>, and releases the lever L carrying the contact-spring K. The contact-springs H, H<1> are then pressed together by the spring N acting on the lever L, and the bell circuit on the engine is closed. The apparatus is reset by the driver. [Reference has been directed under Section 7 of Patents &c. Act, 1907, to Specifications No. 3419,- A.D. 1900, and No. 13,788, A.D. 1904.]

Improvements in Ball or Float Valves.
column13: 3772. Carr, J. F. Feb. 15. Ball and float valves; casings; spindles.-A ball and float valve is constructed so as to be closed by the pressure of the fluid and opened by the weight of the ball or float. Fig. 1 is a section of the valve and its connections, and Fig. 2 is an end view of the valve. A three-winged valve d is seated on a washer e in the valve body, the valve being normally closed by the pressure of the fluid entering through an inlet b connected to the water main. The valve is opened by a screwed spindle f, of quick pitch, which embraces the arm g of a lever connected to the ball, the leverage of the ball being adjustable by means of a set-screw h securing the arm g. As the cistern empties, the ball falls and the arm g, rotating, turns the screw f, which bears on a pin k projecting from the centre of the valve, and forces the valve off its seat. The spindle f may be plain and provided with one or more pins on it working in corresponding elliptical grooves cut out or stamped in a sleeve so as to form a varying screw. The pins may alternatively be on the sleeve, and the spindle may be grooved. The valve closes by the pressure of the fluid from the main, and in case the main is turned off, a spring i is provided for closing the valve. The valve may be actuated by an ordinary ball lever working on a suitable fulcrum, and operating the valve by means of a smaller lever.

column12: Improvements in Horse Breakers and Starting Machines.
column13: 7505. Carr, J. F. April 11. Races, starting.-Relates to apparatus for starting horses, stated to be applicable also for breaking thoroughbreds for racing. Fig. 1 shows a front view, and Fig. 3 an end view, of the apparatus. A frame 1 of the form shown. fitted with flanged wheels 3 running on lateral rails 4, carries a series of depending partitions 15, which form separate stalls for the horses. The partitions slide in grooves which limit their forward motion, while arms on a spring-controlled shaft prevent their backward movement. The horses are kept in the stalls by barriers 29, which, when released, are drawn back by springs into cases fitted to alternate partitions 15. The barriers have rings 31 on their ends, to engage sliding rods 33 working in eyes 32 on the partitions 15. These rods are raised, to release the horses, by the action of electromagnets 5. The armatures 6 of the magnets are connected to spring-controlled bell-crank levers 7 carrying hooks 9, which engage arms on a rocking shaft 10. The shaft 10, when released by energizing the magnets, is drawn backwards by springs, thus raising a rod 14, which is mounted in arms 13 on the shaft 10. The rod 14-as it rises, lifts the turned-over ends 34, Fig. 7, of the sliding rods 33, and frees the barriers. The partitions are padded as at 36, to prevent injury to the horses.

column12: System and method for calibrating an energy meter
column13: A system for calibrating an energy meter is provided. The energy meter has a rotor which rotates at an angular velocity generally proportional to the energy input to the meter. A reference transducer receives an energy input for generating a reference signal having a predetermined parameter, such as frequency, generally proportional to the energy input. A test apparatus is responsive to rotation of the rotor to generate a test signal having a predetermined parameter, such as frequency, generally proportional to the angular velocity of the rotor. An error signal generator receives the reference signal and the test signal upon fractional rotation of the rotor and generates an error signal to indicate the amount of error between the frequency of the test signal and a calibration value corresponding to the frequency of the reference signal. The meter is calibrated based on the error signal. A related method is also disclosed for calibrating the meter.

column12: Flow reduction attachment for storage vessel
column13: This is a new and useful improvement to liquid and dry product containers, modifying the flow rate of delivery. The user sandwiches the invention between the cap and existing vessel, which reduces the delivery rate of the product from the container when poured by the user. The invention conserves product quantity and reduces loss in an accidental spill. The invention is designed to fit a variety of containers. The invention is designed to dispense different products at desired flow rates. The invention is designed to be modified for specific applications. column12: A Mechanism for use with a Knitting Machine
column13: 1,173,001. Knitting machines; spinning and twisting machines and processes. J. C. DOUGHTY. 14 Nov., 1967 [11 Oct., 1966], No. 45375/66. Headings D1C; D1D and D1F. In apparatus for marling or twisting yarns into composite yarn prior to feeding the latter to the knitting elements of a knitting machine, single or composite yarn(s) drawn from initial package(s) is/are augmented by yarn(s) drawn from successive further package(s) and the rotation of the package support(s) is/are determined and controlled, so as to achieve regulation or variation in such factors as colour pattern, bulk, texture, count, twist value and direction, in the composite final or intermediate yarn(s), and/or throughout speed or rate of yarn consumption by the machine, in accordance with the operating requirements of the knitting machine and the fabric it is producing. Examples of yarn include braid ribbon, knitted cords or strips, slub, elastic, metal or metallised yarns and yarns of man-made fibre, wool, silk and cotton. The variation in twist may be controlled automatically e.g. from pattern tapes, cards or chains at the main control position of the machine. A reciprocating motion, derived from such parts as the cam box carriage, yarn feeder or sinker operative mechanism of the machine, may be converted into a unidirectional rotary movement of package supports. In the apparatus shown associated with a flat knitting machine, movements of carriage 30 is transmitted through "bow" 29 and spring-plunger coupling 28 to a slider 26 which moves along a bar 27 to move correspondingly endless belts 16 and 21' connected thereto by coupling block 20 and entrained around rotary pulleys 17 and 22 and separate grooves in a pulley 18. At the extremity of each reciprocatory movement of slider 26, a roller 35 on a finger piece 34 engages a cam face 36 of adjustably positioned cam member 33 thereby rotating cam shaft 32, in one direction at one extremity and in the reverse direction at the other extremity. This rotation is transmitted through lever 37, linkage 38, a pair of levers 39 and 40, to advance or retract pairs of pulleys 41 and 42 and thus force a run 24 or 25 of the belts into driving engagement with one side or the other of pulley 15 so that layshaft 12 is continuously rotated in one direction, as are the package supports such as 6 driven therefrom by pulley 13 and belt(s) 14 or cross-belt(s) (not shown). In the arrangement shown in Fig. 4, yarns withdrawn from, say three, static or rotating packages 45 pass through, say four, axially aligned bores 53 in package supports 51 and are enjoined by or twisted with yarns supplied successively from packages 55. Each support is driven, through belt (or cross belt) and pulley, by an individual, manually or automatically reversible, electric motor 58 (which may be preset to a particular speed characteristic). The motors may be individually or collectively subject to overriding speed control by signal(s) derived, for example, from a tachogenerator, as at 60, or photo-electric device(s) (not shown) measuring the speed of final yarn 63 fed to the machine, and operating through eddy-current couplings. All the mechanical and/or electrical drives shown may be replaced by pneumatic or hydraulic transmissions (not shown).

column13: A vehicle theft prevention device (10) arranged to be fitted to the air inlet/outlet of a vehicle tyre includes a motion detector (11) and an air release means (12). column13: The present invention provides an implantable neuromodulation system for delivering an electrical signal to a nerve to stimulate, inhibit or block conduction of action potentials in the nerve. The system comprises a neural interface device comprising first and second electrodes; a signal generator and a first closed-loop controller configured to generate a control signal based a property of the signal based on a measured voltage across the first and second electrodes, and cause the signal generator to adjust the electrical signal to modify the property of the signal.

column12: Methods and apparatus for redirecting requests for content
column13: The invention is directed to techniques in a computer, for processing a content request. In one arrangement a content engine receives a content request from a client, generates a result based on the content request, the result including one of a content-providing value and a redirection value in response to the content request, and selectively provides, to the client, one of (i) content when the result includes the content-providing value, and (ii) a redirection message when the result includes the redirection value, the redirection message including an extended domain name having a client identifier which identifies the client. The result can be used by a content router or content engine in deciding whether to provide content or a redirection. The decision to selectively provide can be based on client proximity to the content engines, past redirections, content size and type, content engine capacity, content availability and other factors.

column12: Managing a content distribution system using virtual content-distribution trees
column13: A technique can be used to obtain content (e.g., a live feed, pre-positioned content, etc.) from a content-originating device (a content source). The technique involves identifying a tree-based location-path having a series of locations which leads from the computerized device to the content-originating device. Each location includes a set of devices, and the set of devices of at least one location includes multiple devices. The technique further involves selecting a device-path from the computerized device to the content-originating device based on the identified location-path, and acquiring the content from the content-originating device from at least one of the devices along the selected device-path. The selected device-path includes at least one device of each location of the series of locations.

column13: A mobile peat cutting and dewatering machine capable of operating in the peat bog which comprises at the front of the machine a peat harvesting device capable of removing a few centimetres of peat from the bog, a peat press mounted on tracks, which is fed by transport means from the peat harvesting device, and means for the removal of pressed peat from the mobile machine. The tracks are suitably caterpillar tracks of dimensions such that the track loading of the machine is less than 2.8 pounds per square inch. The peat harvesting device is suitable a transverse scraper screw capable of removing 3-10 centimetres of peat from the surface of the peat bog, which levels the surface of the peat bog for the tracks of the machine. The water released from the peat in the peat press is suitably collected and recycled to wash the rollers of the peat press.

column12: Personal thermal comfort system using thermal storage
column13: The present invention is directed to method and apparatuses for modifying the air of a localized zone to suit personal comfort. This invention includes the heating or cooling of the air in the localized zone with a novel apparatus and inhibiting the concurrent release of byproduct air at undesirable temperatures while using a heat pump. column12: Improvements in Means or Apparatus for Automatically Starting, Controlling, and Stopping Single or Multiphase Alternating Current Electric Motors.
column13: 28,687. Carr, O., and Birch, J. C. Dec. 29. Motors, controlling. -In order that the requisite current may be supplied to the armature of an alternating-current series or repulsion motor both at starting and during running, the position of the brushes upon the commutator is automatically d etermined by means of a centrifugal governor or the like driven by the armature shaft, which serves, in addition, to open-circuit the motor upon the occurrence of an overload or a failure of current. The overload and no-voltage release arrangements are shown also in their application to induction motors. Within the end casing C, Fig. 3, of the motor and upon the armature shaft G is fixed a disc O, provided with two or more radial slots P, within which slide pins Q connected to governor balls R mounted on levers S pivoted to a sliding sleeve T. Pins V at the extremities of a forked lever W enter into an annular groove in the sleeve T, and the lower end of the lever W is provided with a spur-sector 2 gearing with a pinion 3 on a screw-threaded shaft 4, which works through a swivelling nut fixed to one of the arms of the brush-rocker N, so that, as the sleeve T moves along the shaft, the brushes are moved around the commutator. When the sector 2 is moved away from the commutator, a projection 8 thereon bears upon a switch arm 7, and completes the motor circuit between the terminals I, J. Upon the occurrence of an overload or a failure of the supply, the centrifugal governor moves the sector back, and the projection 8 engages with a projection 9 on the arm 7, thereby opening the switch. The brushes are brought into the best position for starting, and the switch 7 is closed by pressing the upper end of a lever Y pivoted on the brush-rocker handle or on a spindle Z and with its lower end in a position for moving the sleeve T. Fig. 2 shows an induction motor, in which one end of the lever W works in the annular groove U of the sleeve T and the other end between projections 11, 12 on the switch arm 7, which is adapted to make contact with the terminals I, J. Springs 13, 14 connect the levers W, 7.

A method for the manufacture of bleach activators is provided. The process comprises dissolving an acid halide or anhydride in a water miscible hydroxyl-free solvent prior to reaction with an aqueous dispersion of an aryl hydroxysulphonate. The aqueous dispersion additionally comprises an alkali, especially sodium hydroxyde. The preferred organic solvent is acetone. The process is particularly suited to the situation where the acid halide or anhydride is a solid or poorly soluble in water and in such situations can offer improvements in yield over the processes of the prior art.

The improved dredge floating pontoon pipe-line ball joint disclosed is adapted for releasably connecting adjacent ends of two conduit sections which are part of a dredge line. The improved ball joint includes: a ball member secured to an end of one of the conduit sections; a socket member secured to an end of the other conduit section and adapted to fit about at least a portion of the ball member; and a ring mounted on the ball member and moveable with respect to and on the ball member so as to permit relative, universal movement between the two conduit sections. A plurality of retention pins are carried by the ring at spaced intervals about the ring and are utilized to retain the ring on the ball member particularly during assembly and disassembly of the improved joint. A novel cooperating hook member and lug arrangement is utilized for locking the ring and socket member together, and for interconnecting the ends of the conduit sections. This arrangement includes a novel means for preventing accidental unlocking of the ring and socket member during usage.

column12: Retaining assembly to attach one or more mobile devices to a mobile object
column13: A retaining assembly to attach one or more mobile devices to a mobile object. The retaining assembly may include a mounting plate that attaches to the mobile object by way of a mounting bracket or scorecard clip-on. The mounting bracket provides dovetails for selecting engaging the mounting plate in different orientations. The mounting plate facilitates various magnetized components to removably attach to the mobile device. If the mobile device has a third-party extensible grip, a retaining ring may be employed to attach the mobile device or the extensible grip modified to one of the various magnetized components.

column12: CHLORINE PRODUCING/CONSUMING PLANT COMPRISING A ZINC-CHLORIDE BATTERY
column13: An improved chlorine-producing plant having at least one electrolytic cell adapted to generate chlorine in combination with a zinc-chloride battery stack and electrolyte circulation system is disclosed. Conduit means is provided for permitting the chlorine generated by the battery stack during the charging of the battery stack to supplement the amount of chlorine generated by the electrolytic cell, and for permitting the electrolytic cell to supply chlorine to the battery stack during the discharge of the battery stack. Additionally, power conditioning means may be interposed between the electrolytic cell and the zinc-chloride battery stack for permitting the zinc-chloride battery stack to supplement the supply of electrical power to the electrolytic cell during the discharging of the battery stack. In operation, the zinc-chloride battery stack is charged substantially during off-peak electrical energy consuming hours and discharged substantially during on-peak electrical energy consuming hours. The principles of the present invention are also applicable to chlorine consuming plants having a means for conveying chlorine from a source of chlorine, such as a tank car containing liquidified chlorine. A zinc-chloride battery stack is provided in combination with conduit means for permitting the chlorine generated by the battery stack during the charging of the battery stack to supplement the amount of chlorine to the chlorine consuming plant, and for permitting the conveying means to supply chlorine to the battery stack during the discharging of the battery stack.

column12: AN IMPLANTABLE NEUROMODULATION SYSTEM UTILISING CLOSED LOOP CONTROL
column13: The present invention provides an implantable neuromodulation system for delivering an electrical signal to a nerve to stimulate, inhibit or block conduction of action potentials in the nerve. The system comprises a neural interface device comprising first and second electrodes; a signal generator and a first closed-loop controller configured to generate a control signal based a property of the signal based on a measured voltage across the first and second electrodes, and cause the signal generator to adjust the electrical signal to modify the property of the signal.

column12: RETAINING ASSEMBLY TO ATTACH ONE OR MORE MOBILE DEVICES TO A MOBILE OBJECT
column13: A retaining assembly to attach one or more mobile devices to a mobile object. The retaining assembly may include a mounting plate that attaches to the mobile object by way of a mounting bracket or scorecard clip-on. The mounting bracket provides dovetails for selecting engaging the mounting plate in different orientations. The mounting plate facilitates various magnetized components to removably attach to the mobile device. If the mobile device has a third-party extensible grip, a retaining ring may be employed to attach the mobile device or the extensible grip modified to one of the various magnetized components.

column12: METHODS AND APPARATUS FOR REDIRECTING REQUESTS FOR CONTENT
column13: A content engine receives a content request from a client, generates a result including one of a content-providing value and a redirection value in response to the content request, and selectively provides, to the client, one of (i) content when the result includes the content-providing value, and (ii) a redirection message when the result includes the redirection value, the redirection message including an extended domain name having a client identifier which identifies the client. The result can be used by a content router or content engine in deciding whether to provide content or a redirection. The decision to selectively provide can be based on client proximity to the content engines, past redirections, content size and type, content engine capacity, content availability and other factors.

column12: Methods and apparatus for obtaining content from a content-originating device within a computerized network
column13: A technique can be used to obtain content (e.g., a live feed, pre-positioned content, etc.) from a content-originating device (a content source). The technique involves identifying a tree-based location-path having a series of locations which leads from the computerized device to the content-originating device. Each location includes a set of devices, and the set of devices of at least one location includes multiple devices. The technique further involves selecting a device-path from the computerized device to the content-originating device based on the identified location-path, and acquiring the content from the content-originating device from at least one of the devices along the selected device-path. The selected device-path includes at least one device of each location of the series of locations.

column13: 14,927. Storey, H., and Carr, J. D. June 23. Cutting ladder tapes for window blinds.-In woven ladder tapes for venetian blinds, as they come from the loom, the warps of the cross tapes cross at intervals from one main tape to the other without being intersected by weft threads. The invention consists in a machine for cutting out these unintersected warp threads. The tape is drawn through the machine by any suitable means and, by the contact of the uncut warp threads D with its teeth C, imparts rotation to the disk B, which is geared to a cam-disk F whereby the cutters are operated. The jaw J with its cutter L is first lowered between the main tapes by the action of one of the cams on the lever O; the cross warps now move up against the jaw, which is capable of a slight movement in the carriage N, parallel with the tape, under the control of a spring P<1>. The jaw K, which is likewise mounted on the carriage N and is supported by a lever Q to which is jointed a link R<2>, is now brought down to sever the threads, by the action of a cam upon a roller R at the end of the link R<2>. The cutting-device is then moved upward by the spring N' acting on the carriage N. Instead of cutters, electrically-heated wires may be used to burn through the threads.

column12: ZINC CHLORINE BATTERY IN A CHLORINE PRODUCING/CONSUMING PLANT
column13: An improved chlorine producing plant having at least one electrolytic cell adapted to generate chlorine in combination with a zinc-chloride battery stack and electrolyte circulation system is disclosed. Conduit means is provided for permitting the chlorine generated by the battery stack during the charging of the battery stack to supplement the amount of chlorine generated by the electrolytic cell, and for permitting the electrolytic cell to supply chlorine to the battery stack during the discharge of the battery stack. Additionally, power conditioning means may be interposed between the electrolytic cell and the zincchloride battery stack for permitting the zinc-chloride battery stack to supplement the supply of electrical power to the electrolytic cell during the discharging of the battery stack. In operation, the zinc-chloride battery stack is charged substantially during off-peak electrical energy consuming hours and discharged substantially during on-peak electrical energy consuming hours. The principals of the present invention are also applicable to chlorine consuming plants having a means for conveying chlorine from a source of chlorine, such as a tank car containing liquified chlorine. A zincchloride battery stack is provided in combination with conduit means for permitting the chlorine generated by the battery stack during the charging of the battery stack to supplement the amount of chlorine to the chlorine consuming plant, and for permitting the conveying means to supply chlorine to the battery stack during the discharging of the battery stack.

column13: 27,814. Hogg, A., and Carr, T. J. Dec. 11. Hulls; frames and framing; plating. - The plating of ships' skins, bulkheads, and decks is corrugated and combined with widely-spaced strong transverse frames. The transverse web frames b are made to fit closely to the corrugated plating a and the deck beams h may be closely spaced or spaced the same as the frames. Towards the ends of the vessel the corrugations merge into the normal surface of a ship's hull. The tank-tops t may also be corrugated as shown. Stringers are fitted continuously or intercostally. Longitudinal girders are fitted under the decks, which may be corrugated both transversely and longitudinally. The bottom of the vessel is uncorrugated and the floors are spaced at about half the spacing of the frames. The bulkheads are stiffened with web-stiffeners.

A method for the manufacture of bleach activators is provided. The process comprises dissolving an acid halide or anhydride in a water miscible hydroxyl-free solvent prior to reaction with an aqueous dispersion of an aryl hydroxysulphonate. The aqueous dispersion additionally comprises an alkali, especially sodium hydroxyde. The preferred organic solvent is acetone. The process is particularly suited to the situation where the acid halide or anhydride is a solid or poorly soluble in water and in such situations can offer improvements in yield over the processes of the prior art.

column12: METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR PERSONALLY CONTROLLED SHARING OF MEDICAL IMAGE AND OTHER HEALTH DATA
column13: A method and apparatus for personally controlled sharing of medical image and other health data are disclosed. According to one aspect, the subject matter described herein includes a method for patient mediated access to patient health information maintained by different healthcare facilities and other health record repositories. The methods includes, using a central key server and a plurality of data servers local to healthcare facilities and other health record repositories. At the central key server, a patient controlled registry of access keys that control access to patient health information maintained by different healthcare facilities is provided. The central key server receives, from a data server of a first healthcare facility, a request for an access key that controls access to health information for a patient maintained by a second healthcare facility. In response to the request, the central key server authenticates credentials of the patient and the first healthcare facility, verifies permission from the patient to release the access key to the first healthcare facility, locates the access key for the health information for the patient at the second healthcare facility, and provides the access key to the first healthcare facility. The access key is used by the data server of the first healthcare facility to obtain health information for the patient directly from the data server of the second healthcare facility after successful authentication and verification by the second healthcare facility.

A mobile peat cutting and dewatering machine capable of operating in the peat bog which comprises at the front of the machine a peat harvesting device 1 capable of removing a few centimetres of peat from the bog, a peat press mounted on tracks 5, which is fed by transport means 2,3 from the peat harvesting device, and means for the removal of pressed peat from the mobile machine. The tracks are suitably of dimensions such that the track loading of the machine is less than 2.8 pounds per square inch. The peat harvesting device is suitable a transverse scraper screw capable of removing 3-10 centimetres of peat from the surface of the peat bog, which levels the surface of the peat bog for the tracks of the machine. The water released from the peat in the peat press is suitably collected and recycled to wash the rollers of the peat press. <IMAGE>

column13: The present invention is directed to method and apparatuses for modifying the air of a localized zone to suit personal comfort. column13: The Village Wall system utilizes furniture, equipment, components, and accessories in the creation of unique office designs. Work areas without walls are defined by the location of the work surface along the existing wall.

column13: An osmotic delivery system for controlled delivery of a beneficial agent includes an implant capsule having a beneficial agent reservoir, an osmotic agent which expands on contact with fluid imbibed through a permeable membrane retained by the implant capsule, a delivery port, and a valve for opening and closing the delivery port. Improvements in or relating to a process for curing epoxy resins
column13: An improvement in or modification of a process for curing an epoxy resin having an average number of epoxy groups per molecule of more than one, comprises curing the epoxy resin with at least one amino compound containing primary and/or secondary amino groups in the molecule in the presence of salicylic acid dissolved in an alcohol having a boiling range above 150 DEG C. or in the presence of lactic acid. Specified epoxy resins are the reaction products of epichlorohydrin or dichlorohydrin with polyhydric phenols, polyhydric alcohols or phenol-aldehyde condensates, many being specified. Reactive diluents containing one or more epoxy groups per molecule, e.g. glycidyl ethers of monohydric phenols or alcohols, g -butyrolactone and diethylene glycol monomethyl ether may be incorporated in the reaction mixture. Specified amino compounds are m-phenylene diamine, diamino diphenyl methane, diethylene triamine, aminopolyamides derived from aliphatic polyamines and polymerized fatty acids, polyamine derivatives of long chain fatty acids and adducts of amines and epoxidized oils or alkenes. Specified alcohols are tetrahydrofurfuryl alcohol, furfuryl alcohol, ethylene glycol, diethylene glycol monomethyl ether, diethylene glycol monoethyl ether and triethylene glycol monoethyl ether. Plasticizers, e.g. dioctyl phthalate may be present in the composition. Many examples are given.

An ice body dispenser arranged to provide preselected different quantities of ice bodies from a storage chamber as a function of the size of a receptacle, or cup, placed in a receiving position below a delivery duct thereof. The dispenser includes one or more control elements selectively insertable into the delivery duct to correspondingly adjust the amount of ice bodies delivered by a concurrent opening of the lower closure member of the device. The device includes control switches which sense the size of the cup placed in the ice body receiving position so as to cause a selective use of the different control elements. The control elements may be fork elements having one or more tines for providing improved column interception with effectively minimal crushing and breaking of the ice bodies in the column.

column12: Computerized solid state energy meter test system and method of testing
column13: A portable energy meter test system for testing energy meters and other related instrumentation on-site is disclosed. The test system utilizes waveform generating circuitry to generate and transmit electrical waveforms to an energy meter to be tested, and sensing circuitry for sensing electrical characteristics corresponding to the transmitted electrical waveform. The test system includes a processor for evaluation and control of the testing procedure. A graphic touch screen is coupled to the processor for displaying information about the energy meter and for displaying test options to the user and allowing the user to control the testing process by touching the screen.

column13: A process for removing suspended particles and at least one ionic species from a feed water stream to produce a product water stream, the process includes the steps of: a) forming agglomerates of the suspended particles in the feed water stream; b) passing the feed water stream containing agglomerated particles through a bed of particulate sorbent material so as to i) sorb the ionic species from the feed water onto the sorbent to provide a loaded sorbent and ii) filter the agglomerated particles from the feed water using the bed of particulate sorbent material as a filtration medium to load the bed with the agglomerated particles, and thereby produce the product water stream; c) removing the filtered particles and the ionic species from the filtration medium; and d) re-using the regenerated sorbent in step b).

column13: Individual printed circuit boards (114) are routed from a panel comprised of an array of printed circuit boards. The individual printed circuit boards are moved as a group, after being routed from the panel (111), to a registration nest (140) for holding the individual printed circuit boards. The printed circuit boards rest in the registration nest until a subsequent processing station is ready to receive a printed circuit board. At the appropriate time, each printed circuit board is moved one at a time to a subsequent processing station. A second group of printed circuit boards is routed from a second panel while the first group of printed circuit boards rests in the registration nest and is moved one at a time to the subsequent processing station. A sensor reads features on the panel or on individual printed circuit boards and the routing program is modified or stopped in response to certain panel features.

A turbocharger variable speed control mechanism for a turbocharger for an engine includes a sun gear of a planetary gear set coupled to a turbocharger shaft, a planet carrier operatively connected to an engine output shaft of the engine, a brake disk coupled to and rotatable with a ring gear, and a brake actuator mechanism proximate the brake disk and mounted to a turbocharger housing. The brake actuator mechanism is selectively actuatable between a non-braking state where no braking force is applied to the brake disk so that the ring gear is free to rotate relative to the turbocharger housing, and a full braking state where a full braking force is applied to the brake disk such that the ring gear is held stationary relative to the turbocharger housing and rotation of the planet carrier is transmitted through the planetary gear set to cause rotation of the turbocharger shaft.

It is known that various loci within the genome affect the susceptibility of an individual to osteoarthritis. The present invention relates to the identification of a genetic region that may contain an osteoarthritis susceptibility locus. A genome-wide linkage analysis was carried out using families affected by osteoarthritis. Results were stratified according to sex and joint affected. This produced evidence for linkage of markers on chromosome 2q. A denser map was then produced using more markers in this region. Transmission disequilibrium analysis of the markers highlighted by the linkage analysis revealed disequilibrium at markers D2S117 and D2S325, indicating the presence of an osteoarthritis susceptibility locus in the chromosomal region close to these markers.

column13: A wireless damper include a register, a controller regulating the amount of air flow provided by the register, and a radio frequency communications circuit. The radio frequency communications circuit provides a signal to the controller to adjust the air flow. A register regulation mechanism opens and closes the register in response to a signal from the controller to regulate air flow through the damper. The register regulation mechanism can be a variable switch, that adjusts the amount of air flow through the damper or a magnetic latch. A battery supplies power to the controller, the register regulation mechanism, and the radio frequency communications circuit.

It is known that various loci within the genome affect the susceptibility of an individual to osteoarthritis. The present invention relates to the identification of a genetic region that may contain an osteoarthritis susceptibility locus. A genome-wide linkage analysis was carried out using families affected by osteoarthritis. Results were stratified according to sex and joint affected. This produced evidence for linkage of markers on chromosome 6 between 6p21.1 and 6q22, indicating the presence of an osteoarthritis susceptibility locus in this chromosomal region.

column12: Method and system for extraction of uranium using an ion-exchange resin
column13: The invention discloses a method for recovering uranium from an acidic leach solution or leach pulp in salt water using an amino-phosphorus resin, wherein the liquid phase of the leach solution or leach pulp contains greater than 3 g/L chloride ion in solution. The resin may comprise a functional group comprising an amino phosphonic group, an amino-phosphinic group, an amino phosphoric functional group and/or a combination thereof. According to the invention the leach solution or leach pulp may be generated by in-situ leaching, vat leaching, heap leaching and/or agitated leaching at ambient, elevated temperature and/or elevated pressure conditions in saline or hyper-saline water.

Osteoarthritis (OA) is a debilitating disease involving degeneration of the articular cartilage of synovial joints. It is known that the susceptibility of an individual to osteroarthritis is affected by various loci within the genome. This invention relates to the identification, using genome-wide linkage analysis, of chromosomal regions on chromosome (16) which are linked to genetic sequences which affect susceptibility to osteoarthritis. Methods and means of determining the susceptibility to osteoarthritis of an individual are provided.

column12: VIRTUALIZATION ENGINE AND METHOD, SYSTEM, AND COMPUTER PROGRAM PRODUCT FOR MANAGING THE STORAGE OF DATA
column13: A storage management method for use in a storage area network is provided. The storage area network comprises a plurality of host data processors coupled to a virtualization engine, which is coupled to a plurality of physical storage media. Each physical storage media is assigned a tier level. The method comprises storing a threshold storage access value associated with each tier level, presenting virtual disk(s) to a host data processor and receiving I/O requests to the virtual disk from the host data processor. Additionally, metadata is stored which identifies the tier level of the physical storage to which the block corresponds, mappings between the block and blocks of a virtual disk, and an access rate to the data. The access value is periodically compared to at least one threshold rate associated with its tier level. Depending on the result, storage block(s) may be marked for migration to another tier level.

column13: FIELD: chemistry.SUBSTANCE: invention relates to a method for the reduction of scandium and scandium-containing ions from a feed stream, which can be, but is by no means limited to, a leach liquor or leach pulp. Method comprises reacting a feed stream with an ion exchange resin to sorb scandium or ions containing scandium, from the feed stream into the ion exchange resin under acidic conditions to form a loaded resin, wherein the ion exchange resin is an amphoteric resin, treating the loaded resin with a neutralising solution that deprotonates the loaded resin, wherein the neutralising solution after deprotonating the loaded resin is lean in scandium and ions containing scandium, and wherein the neutralising solution is an alkaline neutralising solution, treating the loaded resin with an alkaline neutralising solution so that the alkaline neutralising solution, which interacts with the loaded resin, has a final pH of 6 to 10, and treating of the loaded resin with a desorbing solution to desorb scandium or ions containing scandium from the resin and to form a product stream rich in scandium or ions containing scandium and a non-product resin.EFFECT: invention provides a high scandium recovery ratio.16 cl, 6 dwg, 3 tbl

The storage area network comprises a plurality of host data processors coupled to a storage virtualisation engine, which is coupled to a plurality of physical storage media. Each physical storage media is assigned a tier level. The method comprises providing a storage management policy identifying threshold storage access rates associated with each tier level, mapping blocks of physical storage to corresponding blocks of a virtual disk, and storing metadata associated with a block identifying the tier level of the physical storage to which the block corresponds, mappings between the block and blocks of a virtual disk, and an access rate indicating the rate of access to the data. The access value is periodically compared to at least one threshold rate associated with its tier level. Depending on the result of the comparison, a storage block may then be marked for migration to a physical storage medium of another tier level.

It is known that various loci within the genome affect the susceptibility of an individual to osteoarthritis. The present invention relates to the identification of a genetic region that may contain an osteoarthritis susceptibility locus. A genome-wide linkage analysis was carried out using families affected by osteoarthritis. Results were stratified according to sex and joint affected. This produced evidence for linkage of markers on chromosome 4 between 4q12 and 4q21.2, indicating the presence of an osteoarthritis susceptibility locus in this chromosomal region.

column13: A storage management method for use in a storage area network is provided. The storage area network comprises a plurality of host data processors coupled to a virtualization engine, which is coupled to a plurality of physical storage media. Each physical storage media is assigned a tier level. The method comprises storing a threshold storage access value associated with each tier level, presenting virtual disk(s) to a host data processor and receiving I/O requests to the virtual disk from the host data processor. Additionally, metadata is stored which identifies the tier level of the physical storage to which the block corresponds, mappings between the block and blocks of a virtual disk, and an access rate to the data. The access value is periodically compared to at least one threshold rate associated with its tier level. Depending on the result, storage block(s) may be marked for migration to another tier level.

RECOVERY OF SCANDIUM USING AN ION EXCHANGE RESIN
column13: The present invention relates to a process for recovering scandium and ions containing scandium from a feed stream using an ion exchange resin. Recovering scandium and ions containing scandiurn in preference to other elements in the feed stream is difficult. The process of the present invention includes: contacting the feed stream with the ion exchange resin to sorb scandium or ions containing scandium under acidic conditions, treating a loaded resin with a neutralising solution that deprotonates the loaded resin, and treating the loaded resin with a stripping solution to desorb scandium or ions containing scandium from the resin. We have found deprotonating the loaded resin allows an emphoteric resin having a higher affinity for the scandium to be used, yet enables effective desorption.

column13: 18,898. Carr, J. W., and Scholes, C. R. Sept. 2. Loom shuttles, changing bobbins and the like in, automatically.-When the weft fails, a fresh cop carried by a holder is automatically inserted into the shuttle from the front, and the spent cop is ejected at the back of the shuttle. A vertical hopper 2 is pivoted at 4 to a frame fixed to the breast beam. The cop holders consist of flat bars with upturned ends, one of which has a cop spindle hinged to it. When in the shuttle, the holder rests on one side, and the holders are placed one above the other with the cops downwards in grooves in the sides of the hopper, and are normally supported by sliding bars 11 pivoted to arms 12 on a cross-shaft 9. When the weft fails, a chain 36 attached to the weft-fork lever pulls back the lower end of a rod 38 pivoted to an arm 39 and having at its lower end a stud which projects into a slot 43 in a guide-plate 44. A slotted jaw 41 is caused to engage a stud on a bell-crank lever 34, which is continually oscillated by a rod 31 and crank 29 on the cam shaft 30. The rod 38 is thus raised at the next upward movement of the lever 34, and by means of the arm 39 turns a rocking plate 17 from a horizontal into a vertical position, as shown in Fig. 7. Slotted arms 19 are pivoted to the plate 17, and are connected by toggle-levers. A spring-controlled pin 24 is connected to the pivot pin of the toggle-levers, and when the plate 17 is horizontal the end 26 of the pin 24 presses against a fixed cam-plate 27, so that the arms 19 are held apart to receive a cop from the hopper. When the plate 17 is turned, the pin 24 is released, and the spring 28 causes the arms 19 to clip the cop holder, which is brought opposite to slots in the shuttle box and shuttle. As the lay beats up, the cop holder is inserted into the shuttle, thereby ejecting the spent cop holder, which is pushed down a shoot into a receptacle. When the rod 38 is raised, its end acts on an arm 15 on the shaft 9, which is partially turned and held by a spring or weighted catch 49 acting on the arm 15, so that the bars 11 are withdrawn from under the lowest cop holder, and similar bars 7 pivoted to arms 8 on the shaft 9 are moved under the cop holders. The lowest cop holder falls on to the bars 7, and when the rod 38 descends releasing the spring or weighted catch 49, and the bars 7, 11 are returned to their normal positions, this cop holder drops into the opened arms 19, which are now in a vertical position, so that it is ready for insertion into the shuttle at the next failure of weft. The bell-crank lever 34 is yieldingly actuated by the rod 31 so that a dwell is given to the rod 38 in its highest position, and a spring-controlled arm 45 acts on the lower end of the rod 38 to release the jaw 41 from the stud on the bell-crank lever when the rod 38 is lowered. The plate 17 may otherwise be rocked by a vertical rod, which is raised by a long lever when a stud on the lever is caused to enter a groove in a cam on the cam shaft by mechanism actuated by the weft fork. The hopper may be fixed, but preferably it is pivoted, and adjustable abutments may be attached to the lay bottom on the hopper so that when the shuttle is inserted the hopper is pushed back, whereby minute adjustment of the movement of the lay is obviated. It is stated that a stop-motion may be applied to stop the loom when the last cop holder is transferred to the shuttle or to the gripper arms.

column13: A seat belt restraint system is provided for a vehicle seat having a seat back extending between a top and bottom portion and a seat cushion extending between an inboard and outboard side. The seat belt restraint system includes a clasp interconnecting an inboard shoulder belt webbing with an inboard lap belt webbing adjacent the inboard side of the seat cushion. The seat belt restraint system further includes a buckle interconnecting an outboard shoulder belt webbing with an outboard lap belt webbing adjacent the outboard side of the seat cushion. The seat belt restraint system includes a buckle anchor mounted to the inboard side of the seat cushion for lockably receiving the buckle. The buckle includes an outboard connect mechanism for realisably locking the clasp to the buckle and define a four point seat belt configuration with the buckle and clasp positioned midway between the inboard and outboard side of the seat cushion. The buckle also includes an inboard connect mechanism for realisably locking the buckle to the buckle anchor and define a three point seat belt configuration with the clasp latched to the buckle and the buckle latched to the buckle anchor adjacent the inboard side of the seat cushion.

column13: The invention discloses a method for recovering uranium from an acidic leach solution or leach pulp in salt water using an amino-phosphorus resin, wherein the liquid phase of the leach solution or leach pulp contains greater than 3 g/L chloride ion in solution. The resin may comprise a functional group comprising an amino phosphonic group, an amino-phosphinic group, an amino phosphoric functional group and/or a combination thereof. According to the invention the leach solution or leach pulp may be generated by in-situ leaching, vat leaching, heap leaching and/or agitated leaching at ambient, elevated temperature and/or elevated pressure conditions in saline or hyper-saline water.

column12: Improvements in or relating to machines suitable for use in the shaping of end portions of shoe uppers
column13: 1,191,264. Boot-making machines. BRITISH UNITED SHOE MACHINERY CO. Ltd. 15 Aug., 1967 [16 Aug., 1966], No. 36519/66. Addition to 931,796. Heading A3B. The machine for simultaneously moulding and out-flanging the heel end portion of a shoe upper of Specification 931,796 is modified in that the inner mould in two parts which are moved apart to tension the upper and means for clamping the upper against the inner mould are replaced by a one-piece mould mounted on a support and grippers mounted on each side of the support for gripping side portions of the upper, the mould being movable lengthwise of the upper relative to the support and the grippers to tension the end portion of the upper. As shown an inner form 500 is slidable on a sleeve 504 through which a heating element 501 passes into the mould. The sleeve 504 is supported by a bracket 506 forming part of structure 510 which is pivoted at 512 to the head casting 1, to allow access to flange-forming members 71 and to facilitate exchanging the inner form for one of a different size, but is normally held in place by springs (522) Fig. 1 (not shown) secured to the base casting 3. A pair of pneumatically-operated grippers 520 are on opposite sides of the bracket 506. In operation, an operator depresses a pedal which opens the gripper jaws; when the pedal is released the jaws close on the upper and move in a toeward direction relative to the mould 500 to take up any slack in the upper. A pneumatic circuit is then actuated to move outer moulding member 9 towards the mould 500 and swing the flange-forming members 71 apart beneath the outer moulding members 9 and then upwardly against them as in Specification 931,796. Air is then supplied to a piston and cylinder arrangement 516 causing plunger 518 to contact an extension 508 of the rod 501. The rod slides heelwards within the sleeve drawing the form along the outer surface of the sleeve, whilst the grippers remain stationary so that the heel end portion of the upper is tensioned and moulded on the form.

A turbocharger variable speed control mechanism for a turbocharger for an engine includes a sun gear of a planetary gear set coupled to a turbocharger shaft, a planet carrier operatively connected to an engine output shaft of the engine, a brake disk coupled to and rotatable with a ring gear, and a brake actuator mechanism proximate the brake disk and mounted to a turbocharger housing. The brake actuator mechanism is selectively actuatable between a non-braking state where no braking force is applied to the brake disk so that the ring gear is free to rotate relative to the turbocharger housing, and a full braking state where a full braking force is applied to the brake disk such that the ring gear is held stationary relative to the turbocharger housing and rotation of the planet carrier is transmitted through the planetary gear set to cause rotation of the turbocharger shaft.

column12: Method and system for extraction of uranium using an ion-exchange resin
column13: The invention discloses a method for recovering uranium from an acidic leach solution or leach pulp in salt water using an amino-phosphorus resin, wherein the liquid phase of the leach solution or leach pulp contains greater than 3 g/L chloride ion in solution. column12: COMPOSITION AND METHOD FOR INHIBITING LIPOGENESIS IN MAMMALS
column13: This invention relates to a composition for inhibiting lipogenesis in animals intended for human consumption after slaughter. There is provided a composition suitable for use in inhibition of lipogenesis in animals intended for human consumption after slaughter comprising a cyclopropane carboxylic acid derivative of formula (I) wherein R is C4 - C16 alkyl, acetoxymethyl or phenyl, one of R1 and R2 is hydrogen, the other of R1 and R2 being hydrogen or -CN, and R3 is -OH, -NH2 or -OR4, wherein R4 is C1 - C4 alkyl, in association with a pharmaceutically or veterinarily acceptable carrier therefor, and the use of derivatives of formula I in inhibiting lipogenesis. It has been found that compounds of formula I have lipogenesis inhibiting activity in animals intended for human consumption after slaughter, especially, for example, in pigs, thereby providing leaner meat after slaughter.

column13: A television signal processing apparatus includes at least one neural network (e.g. 11) for processing a signal representing an image. The neural network includes a plurality of perceptrons (PERC 1,2,3) each of which includes circuitry (W1-W9) for weighting a plurality of delayed representations of said signal, circuitry for providing sums (22) of weighted signals provided by said weighting circuitry, and circuitry (24) for processing said sums with a sigmoidal transfer function. It is known that various loci within the genome affect the susceptibility of an individual to osteoarthritis. The present invention relates to the identification of a genetic region that may contain an osteoarthritis susceptibility locus. A genome wide linkage analysis was carried out using families affected by osteoarthritis. Results were stratified according to sex and joint affected. This produced evidence for linkage of markers on chromosome 11q. A denser linkage map of the region was then produced using more markers. Transmission disequilibrium analysis of the markers highlighted by the linkage analysis revealed disequilibrium at marker D11S937, indicating the presence of an osteoarthritis susceptibility locus in the chromosomal region close to this marker.

column12: Virtualization engine and method, system, and computer program product for managing the storage of data
column13: A storage management method for use in a storage area network is provided. The storage area network comprises a plurality of host data processors coupled to a virtualization engine, which is coupled to a plurality of physical storage media. Each physical storage media is assigned a tier level. The method comprises storing a threshold storage access value associated with each tier level, presenting virtual disk(s) to a host data processor and receiving I/O requests to the virtual disk from the host data processor. Additionally, metadata is stored which identifies the tier level of the physical storage to which the block corresponds, mappings between the block and blocks of a virtual disk, and an access rate to the data. The access value is periodically compared to at least one threshold rate associated with its tier level. Depending on the result, storage block(s) may be marked for migration to another tier level.

column12: A PROCESS AND PLANT FOR TREATING WATER
column13: A process for removing suspended particles and at least one ionic species from a feed water stream to produce a product water stream, the process includes the steps of: a) forming agglomerates of the suspended particles in the feed water stream; b) passing the feed water stream containing agglomerated particles through a bed of particulate sorbent material so as to i) sorb the ionic species from the feed water onto the sorbent to provide a loaded sorbent and ii) filter the agglomerated particles from the feed water using the bed of particulate sorbent material as a filtration medium to load the bed with the agglomerated particles, and thereby produce the product water stream; c) removing the filtered particles and the ionic species from the filtration medium; and d) re-using the regenerated sorbent in step b).

column12: Apparatus having improved cycle time for removing a PC board from a panel
column13: A system having improved cycle time for removing PC boards from a connected panel. In accordance with the present invention, a pair of walking clamps are used to receive a panel from a subsequent processing system, and a movable receiving nest is used to provide the PC boards to a subsequent processing station. The processes of receiving a panel, depaneling the PC board, and delivering the PC boards do not use common components and are able to operate independently and concurrently to reduce idle time in the system and improve the cycle time. The present invention also provides a secondary vacuums which removes debris from the PC boards as the PC boards are being transporting to a subsequent processing system to improve the removal of debris.

column12: Heat sensitive abnormal condition detecting and indicating device and method
column13: A heat sensitive abnormal current condition detecting and indicating device associated with a watthour meter indicates that a possibly damaging surge has been experienced by the meter. The abnormal condition detecting and indicating device includes indicator means retained in normal position by a heat sensitive material, such as solder, with the indicator means being biased to move from the normal position to an abnormal condition position should the conductor being monitored experience a heat rise sufficient to soften the heat sensitive material and release the indicator means. A plurality of embodiments of the heat sensitive abnormal condition detecting and indicating device are shown including a rod maintained in normal position within a tube under spring bias with the rod being movable longitudinally to thereafter extend from the tube to indicate a possible abnormality when a monitored conductor experiences a heat rise sufficient to melt solder holding the rod in normal position, a flag mounted on a rotatable wheel and rod assembly maintained in a rotational normal position with a spring bias thereon so that the wheel and rod assembly rotates to a position wherein the flag indicates an abnormal condition when a monitored conductor experiences a heat rise sufficient to melt solder holding the wheel and rod assembly in normal position, and a spring arm held against the monitored conductor by means of solder so that a possibly damaging surge experienced sufficient to heat the conductor and melt the solder frees the spring load arm to spring outwardly for visually indicating that a possible abnormal condition has occurred.

column13: A polyepoxide with epoxy equivalency greater than 1 and a phenol, is mixed with a curing agent and a phenol to give a composition containing at least 25% by weight of polyepoxide. Both components or the second one only may include an extender oil. Suitable curing agents are:-a primary or secondary amine, a ketimine, an imidazoline (e.g. "Synolide" 960 (Registered Trade Mark), a polyamide of a polycarboxylic acid, a carboxylic acid anhydride. Many suitable polyepoxides are listed. Examples of suitable phenols are cresols, higher alkyl phenols such as dinonyl phenol, dodecylphenol, didodecylphenol, dioctyl resorcinols, 2,2 - bis - (4 - hydroxyl - 3 - nonylphenol) propane. The extender oils are mineral or synthetic. They boil above 150 DEG C. and have a viscosity below 2,300 S.U.S. at 50 DEG C. Examples are transformer oils, lubricating oils, fuel oils, or aromatic extracts of lubricating oil distillates. Either or both components of the composition may include a diluent, e.g. toluene, ethyl benzene, xylene, alkyl naphthalene, chlorbenzene, furfuryl alcohol, tetrahydrofurfuryl alcohols, or g -butyrolactone; or a plasticizer, e.g. fine oil or dilutyl phthalate. The compositions are suitable as surface coatings or binding media. Inert particles, aggregates or pigments may be added. They may be applied to surfaces of concrete, asphalt, asbestos, metal, or wood, e.g. pipes, floors, roads or runways, or used for roofing materials, potting, coating, sealing and impregnating. Examples use polyepoxide A prepared from epichlorhydrin and diphenylolpropane. In Examples (1) and (2) equal weights of a solution of polyepoxide A in mixed isomers of dodecyl phenol with a non-reactive high boiling aromatic diluent; and of a solution of N-amino-ethylpiperazine in mixed dodecyl phenol isomers, an aromatic lubricating oil extract and the non-reactive diluent were mixed together. In Examples (3) and (4) the compositions of the first two examples were mixed with silica sand. Example (5) uses titanium dioxide to pigment a composition similar to those of the first two examples. column12: Polyepoxide curing by polymercaptans plus catalytic co-curing agents.
column13:
Extremely rapid ambient curing of polyepoxide resins and mixtures of polyepoxide resins and polyacrylate esters is achieved by use of a curing system composed of at least one polymercaptan and at least one catalytic co-curing agent which is the condensation product of:
 (a) aliphatic amine or substituted aliphatic amine containing at least one primary aliphatic amine group where the aliphatic moiety is ethylene or greater with (b) at least one amino acid, its corresponding lactam or other amide forming derivative. Optionally, known Lewis Base catalysts for the epoxy/ mercaptan reaction, such as tertiary amines, may also be used.

column12: A container and method of use thereof
column13: A container 2 is provided including a first chamber 18 and at least a second chamber 20. At least one wall of the first and/or at least second chamber is formed from at least two spaced apart wall elements 30, 32. The container can be a vacuum unit for use in a sewage or waste collection system whereby at least one of the chambers is arranged to have a vacuum formed therein. The double wall feature may comprise of three dimensional shapes and/or strengthening means 34, 36 on an external wall of the two spaced apart wall elements. The chambers may be placed one on top of the other in a vertical stack arrangement with a partition 24 placed between the two chambers. The partition wall may comprise of an aperture or inlet/outlet means 44 to connect the two chambers in use. Supporting elements 38 can be included to join the outer and inner wall elements, these supporting elements may comprise of kiss offs. The container may comprise of one or more inlet/outlet means 16 arranged at spaced apart intervals around the periphery of a side wall.

column12: MINING APPARATUS WITH PRECISION NAVIGATION SYSTEM
column13: A mining apparatus includes a miner, a conveyor unit and a steering unit connecting the miner and conveyor unit. The apparatus also includes a heading sensor and a controller responsive to the heading sensor. A first actuator is carried on the miner, the control unit or the steering unit. The first actuator is positioned to a first side of a midline of the miner. Further a second actuator is carried on one of the miner, the conveyor unit and the steering unit. The second actuator is positioned to a second opposite side of the midline of the miner. The first and second actuators are utilized to adjust a connection angle between the miner and the conveyor unit either side of parallel in order to maintain the miner on the desired directional heading.

column12: System and method for automated criteria based deployment of virtual machines across a grid of hosting resources
column13: Some embodiments provide a method. The method interfaces with several nodes of a hosting system to collect statistics that includes available resources of each node for hosting virtual machines. The method identifies a set of nodes with sufficient available resources to host a configuration for a virtual machine based on the collected statistics. The method determines an optimal node from the set of nodes that hosts the configuration with a particular set of performance parameters that yields improved performance than when hosting the configuration using any of the other nodes in the set of nodes. The method deploys the configuration for the virtual machine to the optimal node.

column12: Automated system and method for extracting and adapting system configurations
column13: Some embodiments provide a method for extracting and adapting system configuration. The method extracts a first configuration from a first node of a first hosting system. The first node includes several resources for hosting the first configuration. The method analyzes the first configuration in order to determine attributes of the first configuration. The determined attributes may be relevant to hosting the first configuration on a second node of a second hosting system having several nodes. The method generates a second configuration based on the determined attributes. The method then hosts the second configuration at the second node of the second hosting system.

column12: METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR MEASURING VOLUME
column13: A dispensing system for dispensing material onto a substrate. In one embodiment, the material is dispensed into a cavity of the substrate, the cavity having an unknown volume. The dispensing systme includes a housing, a dispensing apparatus, coupled to the housing, that dispenses a metered quantity of material, and a volumetric measuring probe, coupled to the housing, and positionable over the cavity of the substrate to measure the volume of the cavity. In embodiments of the invention, the volumetric measuring probe includes a concave section having a mating edge that is constructed and arranged to create a substantially airtight seal between the probe and the substrate, a chamber, a first valve, disposed between the chamber and the concave section, a pressure transducer coupled to the concave section to determine air pressure within the concave section, an air inlet port, a second valve, disposed between the air inlet port and the concave section, an air exhaust port, and a third valve, disposed between the chamber and the exhaust port. In one embodiment of the invention, the volumetric measuring probe determines the volume of material dispensed from the dispensing system.

column12: System and method for automated configuration of hosting resources
column13: Some embodiments provide a method for automated configuration of a set of resources for hosting a virtual machine at a particular node in a hosting system. The hosting system includes several nodes for hosting several virtual machines. The method, at a first virtual machine operating using a first set of resources of the particular node, receives a configuration for a second virtual machine to be hosted on a second set of resources of the particular node. The method, from the first virtual machine, accesses the second set of resources to partition a file system for storing the second virtual machine. The method modifies the file system to configure the second virtual machine as specified by the configuration.

column12: MINING APPARATUS WITH PRECISION NAVIGATION SYSTEM
column13: A mining apparatus includes a miner, a conveyor unit and a steering unit connecting the miner and conveyor unit. The apparatus also includes a heading sensor and a controller responsive to the heading sensor. A first actuator is carried on the miner, the control unit or the steering unit. The first actuator is positioned to a first side of a midline of the miner. Further a second actuator is carried on one of the miner, the conveyor unit and the steering unit. The second actuator is positioned to a second opposite side of the midline of the miner. The first and second actuators are utilized to adjust a connection angle between the miner and the conveyor unit either side of parallel in order to maintain the miner on the desired directional heading.

column12: SYSTEM OF DEPOSITS DEVELOPMENT WITH NARROW BENCH
column13: FIELD: mining. ^ SUBSTANCE: escapement transportation facility intended for system of deposits development by flow-line method, comprising module conveyor sections, which are joined together to form conveyor chain. Escapement transportation facility comprises the main frame for support of back conveyor section of conveyor chain. The main frame has the first side, through which additional conveyor sections are added to conveyor chain, and the second side. Accumulating conveyor is installed on the main frame. Driving unit is intended for selective motion forward and backward retraction of conveyor chain. Besides escapement transportation facility comprises ceiling arranged over the main frame. Ceiling is installed at least on one cantilever support, passing upward as joint with the second main frame, so that the first side remains open for addition of additional conveyor sections to conveyor chain. ^ EFFECT: creation of escapement transportation facility used for development of deposits at relatively narrow benches. ^ 11 cl, 10 dwg

column13: An osmotic delivery system for controlled delivery of a beneficial agent includes an implant capsule having a beneficial agent reservoir, an osmotic agent which expands on contact with fluid imbibed through a permeable membrane retained by the implant capsule, a delivery port, and a valve for opening and closing the delivery port. When the osmotic agent expands, a pressure is exerted against a separating member positioned between the beneficial agent reservoir and the osmotic agent. The separating member moves within the capsule, thereby forcing the valve to move a distance such that the beneficial agent can exit the reservoir through the delivery port.

column12: System and method for adapting a system configuration of a first computer system for hosting on a second computer system
column13: Some embodiments provide a method for a server hosting environment having several nodes. Each node is for using one or more hypervisors in order to host several configurations of several computer systems. The method receives a first configuration of a computer system. The first configuration includes an operating system that directly accesses hardware of the computer system. The method generates a second configuration that is based on the first configuration. The second configuration includes the first configuration modified to be operable on a particular hypervisor of a particular node in the several nodes. The method installs the second configuration on the particular node in order to allow the particular node to operate on the second configuration in conjunction with the particular hypervisor. The second configuration accesses a set of virtual hardware provided by the particular hypervisor.
